Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 534515b7ca4cea7dfcf151882bc5987fef3f94d5
Majority of this looks like duplications of existing interfaces from either Inventory or Software.  Please use those instead.
I removed all properties that can be found in existing interfaces.

This seems like the only property that isn't immediately obvious that it is  already covered by another interface.

Just taking this piece in isolation, I'm not sure why this is going into Chassis.
I moved the TrustedComponent to Inventory/Item/.

Does this come from specific language in a standard?  Otherwise, what is "discrete" vs "integrated".  Does this mean embedded in a single pieces of silicon?  What about on a single multiple-chip-module?  At what point does one of these cease being "integrated"?
It refers two different circuit attachment type. I added explanation for Discrete and Integrated in the updated version.
Hi Patrick, thank you for your valuable suggestions! I've addressed them in the updated version. It has been tested with a example dbus daemon. Could you please help take a look? thank you!
Hi Patrick, thanks a lot for the feedback, it is very helpful! Please take a look at my response and see if I got it correctly.
Is this an object_path?
readonly?
Yes, will add it.
It's not pointing to a specific object, but a directory where multiple certificates are located.

Generally we don't put data like this in inventory because it isn't fixed data that comes from hardware.

Wouldn't this be an association?

How is this property planning to be used?

A bmcweb client may send request to ask about where the certificates for a given trusted component are stored, In dbus, it construct the certificates resource directory info based on the CertificatesLocation provided here.

I thought about association. but what needed here is just the directory information, not a list of all associated objects. So I chose to store directory information that is required to construct the certificates resource directory in bmcweb.
All associations need to be documented in both interfaces.  I know it is duplicate work.
will do it.
Please see Software.Version readme for how to handle this relationship.  If  what you're looking for isn't already covered over there we need to have updates to the Software.Version.

Thanks for the pointer! After checking the Software/README, it seems to be a no-op here. It is already handled by the interface defined under Software/Version and Software/Activation. 

By creating an association of type `{active_image,software_version}` between the `Software.Version` and `Software.Activation` under `/xyz/openbmc_project/software/`, and an association of type `{activation,item}` between the `Inventory.Item` and `Software.Activation` under `/xyz/openbmc_project/software/<id>`.  I can find all software image info by listing `/xyz/openbmc_project/inventory/.../<item>/activation` association.
We already have containment relationship documented on Inventory.Item.  We don't need a new one here.
Got it.Will remove it and use containing/contained_by defined in Inventory.Item.
We already have Inventory.Connector.Embedded to handle this information.  I don't think we need an additional enumeration for it.

The ComponentAttachType is still needed here as it provides additional information that Inventory.Connector.Embedded is not intended for.

Inventory.Connector.Embedded describes "An embedded component is permanently incorporated into a larger component or device." When a trustedComponent is embedded into a device(for example, soldered on to it), the ComponentAttachType can still be "Discrete". But when the trustedComponent is "Integrated" into a device, it means it is in one SoC/chip.

This makes a difference from security point view as "Discrete" or solding/wiring attachment expose pins that can be tapped while "Integrated" is a more secure attach type.
@patrick@stwcx.xyz, Hi Patrick,  this patch has also got reviewed by Nan with +1. Could you also help review it again and +2 it if it looks good to you? Thanks!
`readonly`?  `const`?
It should be readonly, updated
The associations have been updated.
This has been rebased, please help take a look. Thank you!
